I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this HTTP application. The source code of the HTML page does not contain anything useful.


Doing a directory search shows the interesting entries above.



Doing a recursive directory search against/r leads to /r/a/b/b/i/t. The source code of this HTML page contains the credential alice:HowDothTheLittleCrocodileImproveHisShiningTail. This looks like a SSH login.

Exploitation


Using the credential alice:HowDothTheLittleCrocodileImproveHisShiningTail, I gained access to the SSH application on the target machine. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like the Python script walrus_and_the_carpenter.py can be executed as the user rabbit. This script prints out ten random quotes from the poem. It uses the module random; maybe I can perform module hijacking.


I created a module called random.py on the same directory that contains Python reverse shell script shown above.


Then I started a listener on port 8444 on my local machine. I executed the Python script using the command sudo -u rabbit /usr/bin/python3.6 /home/alice/walrus_and_the_carpenter.py. In the image above, the terminal on bottom is where I escalated my privileges to the user rabbit from the user alice.


The user rabbit contains an interesting file called teaParty.


I transferred this file to my machine. It looks like it is calling date without absolute path, so I can exploit it.


I created a date at tmp directory which contains the code sudo -i. This allows me to open an interactive shell. And then I executed the teaParty binary. Now I elevated my privileges to the user hatter.


There is a file called password.txt. Is this the password for this user?


And the binary perl has capabilities set. So I used this to open a root shell. GG.
